  {
    "id": "gs-68eb01e65d58",
    "title": "Machine Learning Strategies for Upgrading Turbulence Modelling in Aeronautics Applications",
    "authors": "F Billard, G Laruelle, F Chalot, G Rogé",
    "abstract": "In order to mitigate the shortcomings of RANS simulations for turbulence modeling in a separated channel flow with adverse pressure gradient, an artificial neural network is used to compute a correction to the turbulent stress of a RANS model in the momentum equations. Test cases include the flow over a 2D periodic hill (with varying Reynolds number and hill geometry) and the flow in a 3D diffusing S duct. The training and validation data were obtained by comparison between predictions from the 1-equation RANS model and publicly available direct numerical simulation (DNS) and wall resolved large eddy simulation (WRLES) results for the 2D flow and differential Reynolds Stress Model (DRSM) computations for the 3D flow. The model-based approach was selected to derive the correction terms required for the learning step. Different neural network (NN) structures were implemented and tested. Results show a good ability of the NN enhanced model to replicate the reference solutions. The possibility for geometry or Reynolds number extrapolation was also explored for the 2D case, with the assessment of the neural network's performance on cases on which it was not trained. Significant improvement in the prediction of the extent of the separation region was obtained. Results presented demonstrate a promising step towards the goal of including neural networks in industrial turbulence models to enhance accuracy and improve local design space exploration.",
