  {
    "id": "gs-6f2acd2dfd3c",
    "title": "A synthetic approach for high-fidelity aerodynamic performance optimization of large-scale wind turbine blades based on hybrid deep learning networks",
    "authors": "J Gong, H Zhou, C Yuan, X Huang, G Hu, C Li, L Li",
    "abstract": "The increasing size of wind turbine blades poses several challenges, including higher manufacturing costs, transportation difficulties, and exacerbated aeroelastic phenomena. Optimizing both the aerodynamic and structural performance of large-scale wind turbine blades is essential for addressing these issues. Traditional computational fluid dynamics (CFD)-based optimization methods are hindered by low computational efficiency, necessitating the development of more efficient, high-fidelity approaches. In this study, a neural network (NN)-based approach is proposed to tackle these challenges. First, a class function/shape function transformation method is introduced, inspired by a conventional airfoil parameterization method. This approach is applicable to the distribution of blade chord length and twist angle, reducing the number of variables for a 10 MW blade from 82 to 22, while enhancing the smoothness of the sampled blades. Second, a comprehensive blade optimization method, integrating the parameterization method, is developed. This framework comprises two primary components: airfoil optimization and blade optimization. Each component follows a four-step: geometric sampling, CFD-based aerodynamic dataset generation, NN training for aerodynamic prediction, and aerodynamic performance optimization. Finally, the effectiveness of the proposed optimization method is validated by using a 10 MW blade as a benchmark. Results show that the aerodynamic performance calculation time for both the airfoil and the blade are reduced by 88.6% and 91%, respectively, with a prediction error of less than 1.5%. Furthermore, under the design conditions, the lift-to-drag ratio and the lift coefficient of the optimized airfoil are improved by 5.1% and 6.35%, respectively. In addition, the power and thrust of the optimized blade increase by 1.3% and 12.7%, respectively.",
    "published": "2025-05-12",
    "paper_url": "https://pubs.aip.org/aip/pof/article/37/5/057106/3346784",
